  <p>By the time the 2026 World Cup reached its Round of 16 over the weekend of July 4-6, every team still standing had a way it got there, and the dramatic ways got the headlines. One side survived on a stoppage-time winner — Canada had opened the knockouts by beating South Africa on Stephen Eustáquio's goal deep in added time. Another held its nerve through a penalty shootout. A third came from behind twice. And so the commentary, the previews and the betting chatter reached for the same word: momentum. These teams are on a roll. They are peaking at the right time. You cannot stop a side with this kind of belief.</p>

  <p>It is a wonderful story, and stories are how most of us make sense of a tournament. But it is a poor reason to place a bet, and this piece — which offers no tips and no picks — is about why. The sense that a dramatic recent result predicts the next one runs on two well-documented mental shortcuts, and both of them tend to move the price against the bettor who trusts them. Momentum is a story the bracket sells extremely well. The data underneath it is far quieter.</p>

