  <h2>The hot hand, and why sport keeps testing it</h2>

  <p>The idea that success breeds success — that a performer who just did something well is now 'hot' and primed to keep going — is one of the most studied beliefs in the psychology of chance. It has a name, the hot-hand fallacy, and it has been examined across basketball shooting, football scoring, tennis serves and more. The findings are nuanced but consistent in one respect: the effect people believe in is far larger than any effect the data supports. Much of what looks like a streak is simply what randomness produces over a run of attempts, given a story-seeking mind to read it afterwards. A team wins three in a row and we see a surge of form; the same three results, reshuffled, would have looked like ordinary variance.</p>

  <p>Knockout football is an especially thin place to look for momentum, because the sample is tiny. A team plays one match, wins it dramatically, and then plays one more. There is almost no run to extrapolate from — just a single vivid outcome and a natural human urge to turn it into a trajectory. A late winner tells you a team scored late once; a shootout win tells you it converted more penalties than its opponent on one night, an event we have shown behaves close to a <a href="/articles/world-cup-2026-penalty-shootout-betting-variance-philippines.html">coin flip</a>. Neither is nothing, but neither is the momentum the narrative claims.</p>

  <div class="pull-quote">
    <p>A dramatic win tells you how one match ended. Momentum claims to tell you how the next one will — and that is a much bigger claim than one result can carry.</p>
